<p>Uganda has directed internet service providers to suspend access nationwide two days before the Jan. 15 general election, a vote in which President Yoweri Museveni is seeking a seventh term. Authorities said the shutdown is meant to curb misinformation, disinformation and incitement around the election period. Rights and press-freedom groups argue the move, alongside other pre-election restrictions, makes it harder for citizens, journalists, and observers to monitor and report on the vote.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/eWyAIRTwuyKBoQfhJeN9bqXqkLsCSz1c4yHCM6lKSMN0dws21uEKsQ3Z284LwJWmqlv8Y_Dxdn_3F-FC_G6V4dF8eSKWq_-yuGQyg4T6z_9R5nLQmPo72_pkYlyY9AMkjMho-5Qa4e6F1nXJPqmlb7Y' alt='Residents travel past an electoral billboard for President Yoweri Museveni in Kampala ahead of Ugandaâ€™s 2026 general elections (Jan. 10, 2026).' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Rights groups halted: Ugandan authorities ordered some rights groups to suspend election-related work ahead of polling day, according to reporting on government directives shared with civil-society organizations.</li><li>Media assaults: The Committee to Protect Journalists documented multiple incidents against journalists, including a case in which reporter Ssematimba Bwegiire was electrocuted with a stun gun and pepper-sprayed and later lost consciousness.</li><li>Heavy security presence: Reports described soldiers and other security forces deployed on streets in the run-up to voting, shaping how campaigns and public gatherings have unfolded.</li><li>Election expectations: Museveni, 81, has been widely expected to win again amid opposition complaints about pressure and state control, while challenger Bobi Wine remains a prominent rallying point for many voters.</li><li>Connectivity workarounds: The shutdown affects daily communication and business activity, and some users have sought technical workarounds to stay online as connectivity dropped.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Ugandan authorities/communications regulator: Officials justified the nationwide shutdown as a measure to prevent misinformation, disinformation, and incitement during the election period. (<a href='https://restofworld.org/2026/uganda-election-internet-shutdown/'>Rest of World</a>)</li><li>Government authorities (public rationale): Authorities said the decision was made to prevent the spread of misinformation ahead of the presidential election. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/13/world/africa/uganda-election-internet.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Rights groups and election observers: Civil-society groups said cutting connectivity undermines conditions for free and fair voting and makes independent monitoring harder. (<a href='https://restofworld.org/2026/uganda-election-internet-shutdown/'>Rest of World</a>)</li><li>Press-freedom advocates and journalists: Press advocates pointed to assaults and intimidation of reporters as evidence of a hostile environment for election coverage. (<a href='https://allafrica.com/stories/202601140001.html'>AllAfrica (CPJ)</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/uganda-shuts-down-internet-ahead-of-election-orders-rights-groups-to-halt-work'>Uganda shuts down internet ahead of election, orders rights groups to halt work</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://allafrica.com/stories/202601140001.html'>Uganda: Journalists Assaulted, Internet Shutdown Ahead of Uganda Elections</a> - allafrica.com</li><li><a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/world/africa/article/3339812/uganda-shuts-down-internet-museveni-seeks-extend-long-rule'>Uganda shuts down internet as Museveni seeks to extend 40-year rule</a> - scmp.com</li><li><a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/ugandan-voters-face-soldiers-street-internet-shutdown-presidential-129193873'>Ugandan voters face soldiers in the street and internet shutdown before election</a> - abcnews.go.com</li><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01